  "chapter": {
    "number": 52,
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "content": [
          "Why Do You Boast of Evil?"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "hebrew_subtitle",
        "content": [
          "For the choirmaster. A Maskil",
          {
            "noteId": 4391
          },
          "of David. After Doeg the Edomite went to Saul and told him, “David has gone to the house of Ahimelech.”"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 1,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Why do you boast of evil, O mighty man?",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "The loving devotion of God endures all day long.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 2,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Your tongue devises destruction",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "like a sharpened razor,",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "O worker of deceit.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 3,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "You love evil more than good,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "falsehood more than speaking truth.",
            "poem": 2
          },
          "Selah"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 4,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "You love every word that devours,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "O deceitful tongue.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 5,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Surely God will bring you down to everlasting ruin;",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "He will snatch you up and tear you away from your tent;",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "He will uproot you from the land of the living.",
            "poem": 2
          },
          "Selah"
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 6,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The righteous will see and fear;",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "they will mock the evildoer, saying,",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 7,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "“Look at the man",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "who did not make God his refuge,",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "but trusted in the abundance of his wealth",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "and strengthened himself by destruction.”",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "line_break"
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 8,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "But I am like an olive tree",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "flourishing in the house of God;",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "I trust in the loving devotion of God",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "forever and ever.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "verse",
        "number": 9,
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "I will praise You forever,",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "because You have done it.",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "I will wait on Your name—",
            "poem": 1
          },
          {
            "text": "for it is good—",
            "poem": 2
          },
          {
            "text": "in the presence of Your saints.",
            "poem": 2
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "footnotes": [
      {
        "noteId": 4391,
        "caller": "+",
        "text": "Maskil is probably a musical or liturgical term; used for Psalms 32, 42, 44–45, 52–55, 74, 78, 88–89, and 142.",
